'A small percentage of a really big number is still a really big number.' I think this may apply here to Omicron, where even though the cases are less severe relative to those who get Omicron, there are just so many people getting infected than ever before that there will be a relatively large amount of people getting severely sick or hospitalized during the wave of cases that seems to be peaking still. Further, it would make sense that the fallout of a rise in hospitalizations and deaths are lagged several days after the peak. I project the trend to reach near 12k around January 22 and like @Dillyweed has said, I don't see many reasons to significantly change the trend soon. I guess one caveat is that winter cases last year seemed to peak around early to mid January. On the other hand, it took nearly 4 months for  hospitalizations to return to baseline after the winter surge. This winter's surge, which is ongoing, started 2 months later than the anniversary of the first wave, so perhaps we won't see hospitalization in the US reaching baselines until March 2022 (I would say 50% chance). However, Omicron is different and the question at hand deals with California, not the US. Any flaws on my basic premise or further comments?
