14-day average of hospitalized patients at 5009 on Jan 2, 7 days after 51.5 cases/100k population on Dec 26. Hospitalizations lag cases by approx 7-10 days, so estimating the number hospitalized as a fraction of cases 7 days ago will underestimate hospitalizations as a fraction of cases. So 5009/51.5 = 97.3 is an underestimate of hospitalizations per 1 case/100k population. 12000 / 97.3 = 123 cases per 100k population; thus, if CA sees 123 cases per 100k population, a 14-day average of 12k hospitalizations is all but assured. Moreover, in addition to this being an underestimate based on assuming 7 days between cases and hospitalizations, it's also likely an underestimate because cases to date have been skewed towards younger segments of the population. Because US cases are currently 1.6x last year's peak but have not yet peaked, I don't see how CA can escape seeing more than 123 cases per 100k population = 1.1x last year's peak and hence a 14-day average of 12k hospitalizations. And I don't see how this won't happen before Feb 1, as cases are soaring and will likely reach a 7-day average of 123 per 100k population in about 1 week. And I can't imagine hospital capacity precluding 12k being reached, because >22k was reached last year. I'm still trying to force myself to be at least a little cautious in this forecast, but my real instinct is to put this forecast at 99%. It's almost done, imo.
Also worth looking at hospitalizations in the US: https://ourworldindata.org/covid-hospitalizations
@Anneinak

Things aren't adding up. Initial estimates of R0 for Omicron made it look almost as contagious as measles. However, for this calculation, it was assumed that the serial interval (time between cases in a chain of transmission) is the same for Delta and Omicron. However, evidence is mounting that the serial interval for Omicron is actually shorter (~3d) for Omicron than that of Delta (~4.3d): https://twitter.com/trvrb/status/1474143598476083201
That means that R0 for Omicron will be lower than initial estimates, which is good for humanity. It also means that the peak of the wave will be lower and earlier than previously anticipated. Indeed, the fact that SA cases peaked early and fairly low compared to what one would have expected with an R0 almost as high as that of measles is what made me wonder about this possibility. It appears that London cases may already have peaked, too. A lower peak than what has been predicted so far for Omicron, combined with estimates that the risk of hospitalization is lower with Omicron, suggests that 12k hospitalizations may not be reached with an Omicron wave in CA. However, considerable uncertainty remains, at least in my mind. For one thing, I'm not completely sure that the London wave has actually peaked rather than just exhibited some fluctuation with days of the week, although I probably just haven't look at the numbers closely enough yet. So, for now, I'll keep some weight on bin 4.
